            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Sure, it is possible. The reasoning here is that if the plugin is still active, then there is a chance the user hasn't removed its `vim.pack.add()` call/entry. The code action was designed for the \"deleted `vim.pack.add`, but forgot to `vim.pack.del`\" use case.\r\n\r\nIt can be balanced a bit differently: suggest \"delete plugin' code action for any plugin, but have an extra `vim.fn.confirm()` call for active plugins to confirm force delete and show the \"Make sure to remove `vim.pack.add` call for plugin <name>\" note.\r\n\r\nHowever, I still think that the user command (`:PackDel`, `:packdel`, `:pack del`) with completion is a better UI here:\r\n- Typing `:PackDel <Tab>` will show all non-active plugins that are safe to be deleted.\r\n- Typing `:PackDel! <Tab>` will show all plugins to be force deleted.\r\n\r\nIf the user command is on the horizon, I'd prefer its approach and leave code action as is. But this is not a strong opinion and I can rebalance the delete code action if you think it is better.",
            "commit_id": "8b0fe1be789262d57fb1992180a5487454f0d9a1",
            "created_at": "2026-05-07T08:43:45Z",
